column168: While unloading a trailer at the intermediate truck transfer facility of the intended waste disposal facility, a drum was punctured with the forks of a forklift. column168: On 09/01/2016 at 11:23, personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard discovered GATX 471, a loaded tank car of Methanol, leaking from the bottom of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper SNF Holding Company, the Georgia Environmental Protection Division (report number CTS # 80714), and the NRC (report number 1157875) were notified.  CHEMTREC report number  2016-0901-00148).  SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched to the scene to confine the release.  Hulls Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car to have the bottom outlet valve slightly open, an allen wrench holding the bottom outlet valve handle onto the tank car, and a deteriorated secondary closure gasket.  The issues were identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Stacy Hamlin).  Contractor personnel closed the bottom outlet valve, replaced the gasket, and put a temporary nut / bolt assembly in place to secure the bottom outlet valve handle to the tank car.  The shipper was notified to have mobile repair unit correct before the car can be released in transportation.  A GATX mobile repair unit corrected the exceptions on Sept 9, 2016, and the car was released for transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move or a 7.1.      Cause Code: 148  NARRI: 80

column168: On September 15th 2016 in the evening Michael Raback was preparing to leave Cycle Chem Inc. located at 550 Industrial Drive Lewisberry PA  17339 , phone number (717) 938-4700 with a tanker of Flammable Waste to be disposed of at ROSS Incineration Inc. in Grafton Ohio. During Michael’s preparation he moved the tanker from the facility to the drop lot located at 621 Lowther Road Lewisberry PA. to address a flat tire and retrieve supplies. In doing so Michael did not check the dome on the tanker to ensure that it was properly secured.  The dome was not secured and during the move from Industrial Drive to Lowther Road an estimated 183 gallons spilled onto the road way and the drive way.  The spill was not reported until the following morning September 16th 2016 at around 9am to my office. The area traveled by Raback was checked and a spill was discovered in the area of 631 Lowther Rd.   At this time Cycle Chem Inc. mobilized a crew and cleaned up the locations that the material had spilled onto generating one drum of waste weighing an estimated 124 pounds.  The locations were found because of a dark stain left on the pavement from the material spilling onto the ground. There does not appear to be any contamination of land, water or air but the affected area will have samples taken by All State power vac and remediation completed if needed.   I will be terminating the driver Michael Rabacks employment.  It is company policy to complete a full Pre Trip inspection of both tractor and trailer before moving any asset. Clean Venture Inc. also has a policy to report any spill immediately to a supervisor or manager as soon as it happens. Neither of these policies were followed by the driver. A training session will be conducted for all Clean Venture drivers to review this incident and the policy(s) that were violated.
column169: A training session will be conducted for all Clean Venture drivers to review this incident and the policy(s) that were violated.

column168: At around 0530 on 9/19/16 a Clean Venture, Inc. (CVI) Tractor, and roll off container trailer loaded with 14 tons of PCB contaminated soil (13 ppm PCB), was in route on I-80, to EQ Michigan in Belleville Michigan from Cycle Chem, Inc. (CCI) in Elizabeth New Jersey.   A deer came out into the roadway at mile marker 108 in the Penfield, Pa. area. While attempting to avoid the deer the driver lost control of the truck and it rolled on to its right side onto the center median.     The driver was taken to the hospital for minor injuries not due the hazardous material. At 0745 the PA State police, North central PA. Command closed one lane but did not close the entire highway for approximately 3 hours. Diesel fuel leaked from the tractor and most of the material in the roll off spilled on the ground in median.  All State Power Vac based out of Pittsburgh responded to the spill. PA. DEP was advised of the spill at 0830. The contacts at the PADEP were Tom Mears of their emergency response office; his contact number is 570-327-3722, and Dennis Wolse.    The spilled material was removed on 9/19/16 and 9/20/16, placed in roll off container, and will be shipped to the original destination. The damaged vehicles were towed from the site and returned to their origin in Elizabeth, NJ

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services was found to have a leak in the tanker vessel body upon arriving at the Vickery Waste Management disposal facility. The driver of the vehicle immediately donned the appropriate PPE, deployed a bucket and spill pads, and immediately placed a vacuum on the tank, stopping the leak. The vehicle was then moved onto containment, where facility personnel, donning proper PPE, emptied the tanker, fully rinsed the tanker, and rinsed the affected exterior of the tanker. Facility personnel in appropriate PPE also effected a cleanup of such product as had dripped to the ground before containment, neutralizing the waste, remediating the area, and containerizing the waste for immediate disposal at that facility. The spill was reported to the State of Ohio, report # 1609-72-1869.
column169: Prior to the time the tanker was loaded for transportation, and during in-transit vehicle inspections, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. The stainless steel of the tanker body has already been repaired, and the Deracane fiberglass and resin liner is going to be repaired/renewed by a certified tank repair facility. The tanker will then undergo a complete set of  DOT tank inspections by a certified tank inspection facility before entering back into service. The driver will also be retrained on performing pre-trip and in-transit vehicle inspections.

column168: Driver was heading south on SR 191 South in Green River, Wyoming, Sweetwater County approximately 12:20 p.m. on Sept. 14 2016 when sun got in his eyes causing him to sneeze several times.  When driver recovered from sneezing he drifted to the right edge of the roadway.  He was a lead trailer with a pup trailer attached to the lead trailer.  Both tank trailers were hauling diesel fuel.  When driver noticed the pup trailer caught the edge of the road embankment and was tipping on it's side, he could not recover  the pup trailer and it rolled over on it's right side and was dragging.  Driver stopped immediately and noticed the pup trailer had breached it's compartment and was leaking diesel fuel.  Fuel lost was approximately 3300 gals.  Release duration was approximately 1 hour.  Construction equipment nearby immediately put dirt on the fuel to absorb it.  Our environmental response team finished the clean-up.
column169: Driver has many years of experience driving tanker trucks and doubles and triples.  This incident is the result of unfortunate circumstances that resulted from a sneezing fit caused by sun glare.  Driver was not on phone or otherwise distracted.  Human error.

column168: On September 22, 2016, XPO Logistics (XLA Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a possible hazardous, UN2922, Glycidyl Methacrylate, 8 (6.1), III (PRO#537441155) release. According to Mr. Mcmillan, terminal personnel went to unload the trailer (3150526) from the XSL Terminal, when a strong odor was coming from the trailer. Contractor reports they have found the reported drum and cannot see a visible leak. ERTS requested the contractor perform a PH test on the suspected liquid on top of the drum and the PH result was the liquid was a 6. ERTS has requested the contractor remove the caps from the drum and inspect the seals before the drum is placed in a over-pack if the seals are damaged the contractor will replace them and the drum will continue as is if the seals show no apparent signs of damage ERTS has instructed the contractor to place the drum in a 95 gallon over-pack as a precautionary measure. Contractor reports that the bung on the drum was loose and this caused the minimal release to the top of the drum. ERTS instructed the contractor to clean the top of the drum off and place all impacted absorbents into a container and place in the facility for shipper/ client disposition.    Contractor has accumulated (1) 15 gallon plastic drum of impacted absorbents and placed a pending label and staged i the OS&D .

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, a small amount of material escaped through defective gasket. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used in the clean-up were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all containers used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.  Additionally, the customer has been asked to not reuse damaged gaskets for waste drums and suggested to use certified recon drums.

column168: It was reported that (2) 55-gallon poly drums containing unknown corrosives tipped over in transit and have released an unknown amount of product to the floor of trailer OA3877 and the soil underneath the trailer. Contractors were dispatched to assess the extent and source of the release and clean the spill. Contractors determined the release to be approximately 20 gallons from (1) 55-gallon poly drum on UN3267 “Enviroplus CS.” The bung cap on the drum came loose due to a load shift from hard braking. The bung cap was reattached and the drum was shake tested to ensure no further leakage. The drum had no evidence of other damage. All overturned drums were up-righted, secured, and continued with shipping. Acetic acid was used to neutralize the spill and granular absorbents were used to solidify the release. The impacted soil was excavated and taken offsite for disposal along with the impacted absorbents by the contractor.

It was reported that due to faulty packaging a 55 poly drum of UN3264 Ferric Sulfate was leaking from the cap. The drum released about 2-4 ounces to the top of the drum. An environmental contractor was dispatched to perform site cleanup and to secure the loose cap.

column168: On 9/21/16, while making deliveries at Warner Robinson Air Force Base, in Warner Robinson, GA, it was discovered that a 55 gallon poly drum of UN2810 CEE-BEE A-292 was leaking in an R&L Carriers trailer.  The driver stated that the drum released approximately 3 ounces of material to the trailer floor when the drum was being moved with a pallet jack.  The drum would only leak when pressure was applied to the bottom of the drum via the pallet jack.  The damaged drum released approximately 3 ounces of material to the trailer floor.  NO soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  Air Force Base personnel over packed the damaged drum and cleaned the impacted area.  Air Force personnel accepted the over packed drum and took all waste generated.  There was no remaining impact left in the trailer.  The driver believes the release stemmed from a nail from the pallet that was pushed into the drum as pressure was applied to the pallet with the pallet jack.  This could not be confirmed as Air Force personnel would not allow the R&L Carriers drive to watch the clean up.

The damaged pail released approximately 1 cup of material to the concrete dock floor.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The drum has been staged pending the shippers disposition.  There is no remaining impact following corrective actions.

On September 23, 2016 at 1230 ET, a CTL Distribution driver was driving a DOT 407 Tanker when he took a sharp turn. The turn caused the product in the tanker to push against the wash out cap, causing pressure plug to break and leak approximately 10-gallons of UN3082 Diethanolamine "Sepc Flex NF 1004 Polyt" to the top of the tanker and to the concrete curb of the turn. A contractor was dispatched who contained and cleaned the release by utilizing granular absorbents. HEPACO Environmental, CSXT  emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 6 (plus) 1gallon drums leaked 1 paint product due to being improperly loaded as damaged/salvage/used by origin loading shipper. column168: On September 11, 2016, at 05:57 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Avon Terminal, Avon, Indiana reported that  CBTX 780810, a residue last contained tank car of UN1075, Liquefied Petroleum Gas (propane) was leaking and hissing. Reportedly, there was hissing and has a mist around the top housing. The tank car was isolated from Yard personnel. The consignee and shipper, LOS OLIVOS ALIMENTOS and Markwest, were notified via Chemtrec, report #20160911-0006. Environmental Management Specialists (EMS), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Avon Terminal. column168: On September 15th, 2016, FRA HM Inspector Peter McManus discovered in CSXT Selkirk Yard TILX 315653 a loaded UN1987, Alcohol, N.O.S. tank car to be dripping product from the bottom outlet cap. The tank car was isolated, the shipper RPMG, Inc. was notified by CHEMTREC, report #2106-09-15-00165, shipper rep. Keith Krueger, was notified of the incident. A CSXT Contractor was dispatched to the incident, upon investigation, it was determined that the BOV cap had no gasket and the Bottom Outlet Valve had a drip release by-pass, a new gasket was installed in the BOV cap and it was secured tool tight, the release was stopped.   TILX 315653 has been staged for transloading of the product as the tank car is in non-compliance with 49CFR 174.50 and cannot be forwarded.  Mr. Krueger was notified of the BOV release and has identified a calf car for transloading.    Cause Code: 578 ( 5 points) + 551 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80    On September 15th, 2016, FRA HM Inspector Peter McManus discovered in CSXT Selkirk Yard SHPX 208044 a loaded UN1987, Alcohol, N.O.S. tank car to be dripping product from the top valve housing cover, upon opening the cover the inspector found product dripping from the liquid line mounting flange and the valve housing mounting plate.   The tank car was isolated, and the shipper RPMG, Inc. was notified by CHEMTREC, report #2106-09-15-00165, shipper rep. Keith Krueger, telephone was notified of the incident. A CSXT Contractor was dispatched to the incident, upon investigation it was determined that the mounting stud nuts for the liquid line flange were tool tight and product was seeping from between/at the identified release point, pressure was evacuated from the tank car and the stud nuts re-checked, car was secured. column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: SUNDAY - SEPTEMBER 11, 2016.   MR. CLAY VANGILDER OF XPO LOGISTICS TRUCKLOAD, INC. (XPO) CALLED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC. (EMI) TO REPORT A RELEASE OF BATTERY ACID IN A XPO TRAILER AT THE DOUBLEBEE TRUCKSTOP IN CARLISLE, ARKANSAS. THE AMOUNT WAS UNKNOWN BECAUSE THE TRAILER WAS SEALED AND A RESPONSE CREW WAS NEEDED TO MITIGATE THE RELEASE. MR. MELTON OF EMI CONTACTED A LOCAL SUBCONTRACTOR, ENHANCED ENVIRONMENTAL AND EMERGENCY SERVICES, INC. (E3).    THE E3 CREW ARRIVED ON SITE AND INSPECTED THE TRAILER. SULFURIC ACID WAS LEAKING FROM SEVERAL LOCATIONS THROUGH THE FLOOR THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS SECURED, BY THE SHIPPER, WITH A BOLT LOCK AND THE E3 CREW CUT THE LOCK OFF TO GAIN ENTRY TO THE TRAILER. THE CREW DONNED PROPER PPE AND MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER. THREE BATTERIES HAD SLID OFF OF THE PALLET THAT THEY WERE SHIPPED ON AND FELL ONTO THEIR SIDE. THERE WAS NO ATTACHMENT OF THE BATTERIES TO ANY OF THE PALLETS. TWO OF THE THREE BATTERIES WERE LEAKING BATTERY ACID FROM THE FILL CAPS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE CREW UPRIGHTED THE BATTERIES WHICH STOPPED THE LEAKAGE. SEVERAL PALLETS WERE CRUSHED FROM THE WEIGHT OF THE BATTERIES (2200 LBS. EACH). NO OTHER LEAKAGE WAS FOUND.     CAUSE OF INCIDENT: THE HEAVY BATTERIES WERE NOT SECURED TO THE PALLETS CAUSING THEM TO SLIDE OFF OF THE PALLETS AND FALL OVER DURING TRANSPORTATION.
column169: THE TRAILER DOOR ON THE LOAD OF BATTERIES WAS SECURED BY A BOLT LOCK WHEN IT WAS OFFERED FOR TRANSPORTATION BY THE SHIPPER, ENERSYS DELAWARE. THERE WAS NO OPPORTUNITY FOR XPO LOGISTICS TRUCK, OR THEIR DRIVER, TO INSPECT THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER. XPO RELIED ON THE SHIPPER CERTIFICATION THAT THE LOAD WAS PROPERLY PACKAGED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND ACCORDING TO DOT REGULATIONS.     FREIGHT OFFERED FOR TRANSPORTATION SHOULD BE ABLE TO BE INSPECTED BY THE CARRIER BEFORE SEALING THE TRAILER.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A STRONG ODOR PRESENT AFTER THE FLIGHT HAD LEFT THE LUBBOCK AIRPORT FACILITY. THE AIRCRAFT REACHED ABOUT 3000' AND TURNED AROUND AND CAME BACK. THE PACKAGES WERE OFFLOADED FROM THE AIRCRAFT, AND HELD FURTHER INVESTIGATION. ONLY TWO OF THE SHIPMENTS, THAT WERE ALL PACKED IN ONE PLASTIC DRUM SEEMED TO BE PROBLEMS. THE AIRCRAFT INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 10:25 ON 09-09-2016.  I ALSO PROVIDED INFORMATION TO RYAN POHLKE & STEVEN REDEKER WITH THE FAA AROUND NOON ON 09-09-2-16. THE FAA DID GO BY TO SEE THE PACKAGES THE SAME DAY AND THEY WERE LATER RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE DESTINATION, BUT BY GROUND MOVEMENT AND NOT BY AIR. THEY WERE LATER DELIVERED ON 09-15-2016.

column168: AT 6:12 HRS ON 9/5/16, IT WAS REPORTED THAT CONTAINER EMHU 241040 LOCATED AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY WYLLE TX INTERMODAL YARD WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER. EMHU 241040 CONTAINED SEVERAL SHRINK WRAPPED PALLETS OF "BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID." THE ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE. THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED, AND THAT ONE PALLET OF BATTERIES HAD FALLEN OVER AND THE TOP LAYER OF THE PALLET FELL ON THE FLOOR. NO BATTERY CASES WORE BROKEN. FIVE BATTERIES LEAKED ELECTROLYTE SOLUTION FROM THEIR TOP CAPS. THE BATTERIES WHERE UP RIGHTED, MITIGATING ANY FURTHER RELEASE. THE RELEASED CORROSIVE MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED. THE LOAD WAS NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED FOR RAIL TRANSPORTATION. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO SECURE THE LOAD PRIOR TO THE CONTAINER BEING RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION. FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED. THE CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGO, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS.(PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

On September 07, 2016 driver was parked at a truck stop when he noticed that a (1) 330-gallon poly tote containing UN1791 Hypochlorite Solution "Chlormax" was leaking due to a small puncture on its side. The driver stated that it appeared that the metal cage on the tote was rubbing on the poly side during transit causing the puncture. Approximately 0.5-gallons has released to the trailer floor and underlying asphalt parkinglot. A contractor was dispatched who contained and cleaned the release by utilizing absorbents and a vinegar solution. The contractor also completed a tote transfer. The salvaged material in the new tote was placed on the trailer for the personnel to manage. All generated waste was taken offsite for proper disposal.

NO OUTER PACKAGE MARKINGS STATING PACKAGE CONTAINS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. HELD FOR UNDECLARED FAA INSPECTION. ONE RESPONDER INJURED DUE TO INHALATION AND SOUGHT MEDICAL TREATMENT.

column168: This Container on Flat Car( COFC)was identified as having a leak at the rear of the container. The product was a red dye. The COFC was not placarded when we responded on 09/19. Through a request to the shipper it was identified as having a class 3 flammable in the COFC in excess of 2000 lbs. The billing was updated on 09/20/2016 to reflect the Hazardous Material shipment. The container was opened on 09/21/2016, the tote was located at the rear of the container, a penetration crack 2 inches long was identified on the top of one of the corners which was allowing the release of the product by sloshing. The container showed to have 300 gallons of product still in it. The IBC container was transferred to a new IBC container and will be disposed of by Haz-Mat Response INC per request of UPS Freight. The COFC was released back to transportation after being remediated on the evening of 09/21/2016.

column168: THE DRIVER INSPECTED HIS LOAD AT THE TRUCK STOP AND NOTICED A LEAKING TOTE. UPON INSPECTION HE FOUND THAT A STRAP TO TIE DOWN THE LOAD RUBBED A PEA SIZE HOLE IN THE CORNER OF THE POLY TOTE. ADDITIONALLY THE DRIVER USED ABSORBENTS TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING MATERIAL UNTIL THE HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE IS ESTIMATED AT 3-4 HOURS.
column169: PROPER LOAD SECURING PRACTICES WOULD PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE SORT. UPON OPENING THE BOX WE FOUND ONE GLASS BOTTLE IN A PLASTIC BAG. THE BOTTLE WAS BROKEN AND THE SHARDS OF GLASS RIPPED THE BAG ALLOWING THE SPILL TOP OCCUR. THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN THE BOX IN VIOLATION OF 49CFR 173.27(E). THE FREIGHT WAS HELD FOR AN FAA INSPECTION. SA WAYNE KNIGHT FROM THE MEM SECFO WAS NOTIFIED ELECTRONICALLY.

It was reported that due to a possible forklift puncture, (1) 2000-pound supersac had released approximately 1 gallon of UN2468 "Trichloroisocyanuric Acid" to the floor of trailer 688355 at a customer location. A contractor was dispatched to contain the clean the release and transfer the product to a DOT approved container. The contractor stated that there were (2) damaged supersacs that were torn due to not having cardboard between the sacs and pallet. The wooden pallet caused the two supersacs to tear and release a confirmed 2-pounds to the trailer floor in a 20 x 6 ft. All released materials were swept up and cleaned. The salvaged product was transferred into (2) new poly super-sacs which the costumer is currently accepting along with the other supersacs on the trailer. All sweepings and impacted debris was containerized into a (1) 5-gallon poly bucket labeled as haz-waste DOO1 that the contractor took offsite for proper disposal.

column168: It was reported that due to (2) skids collapsing during transit, an unknown number of 5-gallon metal of pails of UN1263 "Super 16 Paint Gun Cleaner" released an unknown amount of product to the floor of trailer OF0398. The caller stated that the fumes were too strong to assess the extent of the release. A contractor was dispatched to determine the extent of and clean the release. The contractor stated that the release was due to (2) skids collapsing during transit. He stated that the release to the trailer floor had evaporated before his arrival. (2) 5-gallon metal pails were found to have punctures from the pallet collapse. A total of (9) 5-gallon metal pails of “Super 16 Paint Gun Cleaner” had to be held back due to damage. The remaining pails were repalletized to continue with delivery to the consignee. The contractor estimated the release to have been approximately 5-gallons total, which evaporated from the trailer floor before his arrival. The impacted pails were over-packed into (3) 55-gallon metal drums and will be labeled salvage and staged in OS&D for terminal personnel to manage awaiting disposition instructions from the shipper.

column168: At 1050 on 09/28/2016 ERTS was contacted by Roger Arthur from Liquid Transport. column168: At 0705 ERTS was contacted by Greg Holmes from R&L's HFT terminal. It was reported that two 30 gallon drums of ChemTreat BL 1301 fell over during transit. With only a 1/2 cup release, RQ will not be reached. ERTS is dispatching ESI to respond to the site and perform ER cleanup of the release and to replace the seal/cap or over pack the drum is seal/cap replacement is not possible.

column168: On September 15, 2016 the Superior Carriers driver was completing a transfer from his DOT 407 Tanker to an onsite storage tank at the Plant but the driver forgot to close the bleeder valve before completing the transfer. The error caused approximately 30-gallons of Ethylene Glycerol /Anti-freeze to release onto an underlying gravel road on the plants property in a 8 x 20 ft area. A contractor was dispatched who contained, cleaned, and excavated the impacted gravel. A skidsteer was utilized to remove all contaminated gravel and debris which was containerized into a (8) 55-gallon steel drums which were taken offsite for proper disposal by the contractor.

On 9/20/16 in Aurora, CO, a 55 gallon steel drum of UN2056 Tetrahydrofuran was punctured by a fork lift blade during unloading operations at the R&L Carriers terminal.  The damaged drum released approximately 10 gallons of material to the trailer floor and concrete parking area.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the area and overpack the drum.  Granular absorbents were utilized to clean the impacted areas of trailer and parking lot. The damaged drum was overpacked into a 95 gallon steel drum and labeled as salvage with all applicable shipping information.  The waste was taken offsite by the contractor and the over pack was left on site for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 09/21/2016 a 55 gallon poly drum of UN1840 Chemtreat CT arrived damaged at the R&L Carriers terminal in Seekonk, MA.  The drum arrived laying on its side with a small pin hole in its body.  It is unknown how or when the drum had been punctured. The damaged drum released approximately 1 cup of material to the dock floor while being unloaded, there was no apparent release in the arriving trailer. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release and over-pack the drum.  Granular absorbents were utilized to clean the impacted area.  The impacted absorbents were put into a 95 gallon poly drum along with the damaged drum.  The over-pack drum was labeled as salvage with all applicable shipping information.  The salvage drum was staged onsite for R&L personnel to manage.

On 9/23/16 at the R&L Carriers terminal in Wilmington, OH, a box containing (4) 1 gallon cans of UN3066 PSX700 FD Cure arrived crushed and leaking.  The cans were crushed by other freight due to a load shift caused by improper loading.  The damaged cans released approximately 4 gallons of material to the trailer floor.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release.  All spilled material was cleaned with granular absorbents and neutralized with a soda ash solution.  The 4 damaged cans and impacted absorbents were containerized into a 55 gallon poly drum and taken offsite for disposal by the contractor.

At 0710 on 09/14/2016 ERTS was contacted by Brian Rider from R&L's WIL terminal. It was reported that a box containing four 1 gallon bottles of Bulldozer Chemical Cleaner was crushed by the outbound terminal. 1 bottle was impacted and released it's contents to the trailer floor. The BOL lists the material as UN1760, but the SDS from the manufacturer lists it as 1789. The Reportable quantity for Hydrogen Chloride is 5000 lbs / 2270 kg or 1730.7 gal /6551.2 L. With a 1 gallon release, RQ will not be met. Spills in trailers, concrete docks, containment areas, inside buildings are not into environment and not considered reportable, The only reporting required at this time is the DOT 5800 due to PG II of material. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident. ERTS is dispatching SES to respond to the site and perform ER cleanup of the release. An ETA of 2 hours was provided.

The lading from the original freight container was transloaded into freight container CMAU533679 with proper load/block/brace was released to the shipper.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident did not require a Form 7.1.

column168: It was reported that (1) 275-gallon poly tote was punctured by a forklift during loading operations at the R+L carriers terminal in Norwalk, OH. Approximately 15 gallons of material were released onto the concrete dock. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release. A nearby contractor conducted cleanup operations.

It was reported that (1) 350-gallon metal tote containing NA1993 was cracked due to a forklift accident during loading operations at the XPO Logistics terminal in Houston, TX. Approximately 2 cups of material were released inside the trailer. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release. A nearby contractor conducted cleanup operations.

On September 12, 2016 at 0145 ET, during unloading operations, terminal personnel discovered that (1) 50-pound plastic bag containing UN3378 Sodium carbonate peroxyhydrate "Green Clean Pro" was torn by the trailer door while it was opened due to being loaded to close to the door. Approximately 15-pounds released to the trailer floor in a 2 x 3 ft area and slightly on the concrete dock floor in a 1 x 1 ft area. A contractor was dispatched who contained and cleaned the release. All release materials and debris was swept up and containerized into a (1) 15-gallon poly drum as haz-waste. The salvaged bag had been containerized into a (1) 15-gallons poly drum and staged onsite for the terminal personnel to manage.

column168: UTLX 205664 was noted as leaking in the yard by BNSF personnel. Upon further investigation, the tank car was dripping product from the bottom outlet valve. The contractor arrived on scene and noted that the car was a residue car. The bracket that pins the BOV handle in the closed position was sheared off, and this allowed the handle to open under its own weight. The car was also noted as being in a Bad Order status and was being returned to UTLX for Home Shop repairs.   The contractor did comment that the BOV cap and plug were tool tight and the drip was coming from the packing nut on the BOV handle. The manway was opened up and it was noted that there was no product left in the tank itself. The contractor removed the BOV cap, drained the residual that was contained within the BOV and cap assembly, and reinstalled the cap tool tight. There was no further leaking of product noted.
column169: Shipper must ensure proper securement of tank car and packaging prior to releasing for transport. In this instance where the package was known as leaking, the shipper must ensure that all product is removed from the tank car prior to transport to eliminate any future releases of hazardous materials.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: 1727 CT on September 7, 2016 a gas odor was reported by a switch crew on bowl track 42. The odor was identified coming from GATX 78133 which was venting LPG and foaming out of the top hatch. The fire department was called and responded to the release.   1820 The pressure relief device reset while the fire department was on scene and the evacuation was lifted. No product reached the ground, it all evaporated on top of the car. It was determined by the onsite Hazmat responder that the tank car was not overloaded and all appliances appeared to be secured.  It was determined that the car experienced an over speed coupling event resulting in a hydraulic surge of LPG through the pressure relief device.  The car has been released to destination.
column169: It has been determined that this event was a preventable car handling incident. BNSF will re-train the hump tower and switching crews in proper speed of coupling and braking procedures to prevent future similar events.

column168: We received an order to fill a 320 gallon customer owned underground tank.When our driver arrived he found that the tank was out of gas and he performed a leak meter test using a Ferrell meter. Test passed and our driver proceeded to fill the tank. Driver noticed that the tank was taking an unusual length of time to fill so he then stopped pumping the gas and red the delivery meter on the back of the truck. It read 337.3 gallon. He then saw a cloud of propane escaping from about five feet away from the tank up into to air. It was determined that the underground tank had a hole in it. We later discovered that the tank was empty. We red tagged the tank. There was no property damage. No injuries.
column169: The operations manager discussed the incident with his team during his September safety meeting. His team is aware that we must first perform a bar probe test before we will underground tanks that is on zero percent with no vapor pressure. Will set up an underground tank testing training that will be instructed by our vendor gas equipment and the operations manager.

column14: THE ON RAMP HWY 70 TO HWY 29
column168: THE DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO ENTER US HIGHWAY 29 VIA THE TUCKER STREET ON-RAMP. WHILE NEGOTIATING THE CURVE ON THE ON-RAMP, THE TRACTOR TRAILER TIPPED OVER AND LANDED ON ITS SIDE. TIME OF THE ACCIDENT WAS 0936. WHEN THE TRAILER TURNED ON ITS SIDE, TWO TOTES CONTAINING 45% POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE, AND 15% SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE CAME OUT OF THE ROOF OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE HIGHWAY. BOTH TOTES SUSTAINED CRACKS RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT ONTO THE ONTO THE HIGHWAY THERE WAS 866 POUNDS OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE RELEASED, AND 457.5 POUNDS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE RELEASED. GREENSBORO FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE DEPARTMENT WERE THE FIRST ON THE SCENE. GREENSBORO FD PROCEEDED TO DIG SOIL FROM THE SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY TO BLOCK THE STORM DRAIN NEAR THE RELEASE. NO PRODUCT REACHED THE STORM DRAIN. BRENNTAG'S GREENSBORO FACILITY WAS CONTACTED AND BRENNTAG PERSONNEL REPORTED TO THE SCENE. BRENNTAG PROCEEDED TO CONTACT CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES TO FACILITATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE. CURA CONTRACTED WITH A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY, SWS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE, TO CONDUCT THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL CLEANUP. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE INCLUDED SPREADING SAND AND ABSORBENT TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED MATERIAL. SWS PERSONNEL EMPTIED THE TRAILER OF THE REMAINING UNDAMAGED MATERIAL AND PLACED IT ONTO A BRENNTAG TRUCK TO BE RETURNED TO THE FACILITY. ONCE THE OVERTURNED TRACTOR TRAILER WAS EMPTY OF CONTAINER, A WRECKER SERVICE GOT THE VEHICLE UPRIGHT AND THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED TO THE WRECKER COMPANY'S YARD. AFTER THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS TAKEN AWAY, SWS COMPLETED CLEANUP OF THE HIGHWAY. GREENSBORO OPENED THE HIGHWAY AT 1036 PM.
column169: DRIVER WAS SITED FOR EXCESSIVE SPEED CAUSING TURNOVER. RETRAINING DRIVER ON PROPER SPEED WHEN TAKEN SHARP TURNS ON THE ROADWAY. INVESTIGATING IMPROVED LOAD SECUREMENT WITH ALL FACILITIES TO MINIMIZE LOAD SHIFTS DURING ACCIDENTS.

column168: THE DRIVER CALLED ON 09/16/2016 AT 7:55PM TO REPORT THAT HE WAS ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD ALABAMA AND HIS TRUCK ON FIRE. HE WAS TRAVELING WB ON I-22 IN CORDOVA, AL WHEN A COUPLE OF PASSERBYS GOT HIS ATTENTION TO PULL OVER. HE PULLED ONTO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AT EXIT 72 (CORDOVA GORGAS EXIT). WHEN HE LOOKED THROUGH HIS MIRROR, HE COULD SEE FIRE AND SMELL THE SMOKE. ONCE HE GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK, THE FLAMES STARTED TO SHOOT UP COMING FORM THE LEFT REAR HUB ASSEMBLY. HE USED THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER BUT SAW IT WAS NOT HELPING. THE ALABAMA HIGHWAY PATROL, PARAMEDICS AND FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED WITHIN 15 MINUTES ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER.THE TROOPER SAID THAT KILGORE WRECKER SERVICE WAS IN ROUTE, THEY COULD HANDLE THE TOW AND CLEAN-UP. THE FIRE DESTROYED THE TRUCK AND BURNED THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER, THE FREIGHT IN THE NOSE WAS DAMAGED. THE TROOPER ALSO ADVISED THAT THE INTERSTATE WAS SHUT DOWN MOMENTARILY, LESS THAN 30 MINUTES, BEFORE THEY HAD A LANE BACK FOR TRAVEL. THE FOLLOWING DAY, THE TOW VENDOR ADVISED THERE WAS A TOTAL OF 20 PALLETS OF WHICH 1 PALLET WAS TOTALLY DESTROYED AND A SECOND PALLET LEAKING. HE ADVISED THAT ALL THE FREIGHT WAS COVERED IN A SMOKY RESIDUE. HE ESTIMATED THAT UP TO 75 GALLONS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED TO THE DIRT ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD WITH NO DAMAGE TO THE ASPHALT. THE TOW VENDOR ADVISED THAT THEY SCOOPED 4 TO 6 TONS OF DIRT AND LOADED INTO A DUMP TRUCK. THEY WERE ABLE TO OFFLOAD THE FREIGHT ONTO A LOWBOY TO TRANSPORT BACK TO THEIR FACILITY ALONG WITH THE TRACTOR, TRAILER AND DUMP TRUCK OF DIRT.

column168: Bobtail truck was returned to service following maintenance. However, pump and swivel seals dried out during maintenance. During first loading, ammonia leaked from pump and swivel seals. Loading was stopped immediately and leak stopped after about five seconds. Spilled product quickly evaporated.
column169: 1) Remind vendors to not allow seals to dry out during maintenance.  2) After maintenance, apply vapor before liquid during initial fill procedure to better check seal integrity.

column168: On 09/12/2016 at 3434 Silver Lake Road in Castle Rock, WA, a System Transport tanker loaded with UN1719 LFG Scrubber Liquor released approximately 5 gallons of material from a leaking top dome lid. One of the DOT 412 trailers dome lids was not properly secured prior to transport causing the release of approximately 5 gallons of material to a 3 mile stretch of Silver Lake Road.  Once the driver noticed there was a release he pulled to the side of the road where he properly secured the dome lid.  There were no drains, soils or waterways impacted by the release.  There were no road closures or injuries due to the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the roadway and collect all free product.  By the time the contractor arrived on site the material had dried into a powder on the road.  The contractor utilized a street sweeper to clean the impacted area of roadway and collect all free product.  All free product was captured with the street sweeper and all waste was collected into a 55 gallon poly drum and taken offsite for disposal.  The trailer was secured and inspected and determined to be in safe condition to continue with out any further release.

At 10:28 AM on 09/08/16, Superior Carriers driver picked up loaded ISO tank from Akzo Nobel and transported the ISO tank to the Superior Carriers trucking terminal, for storage.  The tank was transported with no product release,  to storage yard at approximately 10:45 AM.  A yard check was completed at 11:45 AM and the ISO tank was not leaking at that time.  At 14:33 PM a Superior Carriers driver passed by the ISO and noticed product leaking from the sealed crash box. The storage personnel cut the wire seals and noticed the ball valve in the open position and the loading flange, not attached. The storage personnel closed the valve, and tightened the loading flange, stopping the product from releasing.  Akzo Nobel loading personnel did not close the ball valve or tighten the loading flange, prior to sealing the crash box with metal seals.  The ISO tank, after sitting in the heat several hours, began to build pressure and pressure pushed the product out of the open valve and flange, filling the crash box and spill damn, located on top of the ISO tank and then began to spill onto the tank and ground.  The product drained into the swampy area behind where the ISO tank was parked at the trucking terminal, storage yard.       Akzo Nobel  was notified and the shipper called a crew out to build a sand dike or berm around the area where the product release occurred. The shipper's crew vacuumed out the water in the diked area and treated the contained area with 250 gallons of 4% hydrogen peroxide.  Soil samples were taken and came back inconclusive.  The shipper's crew again vacuumed more water out of the area and treated the area with more hydrogen peroxide. Additional samples were taken and the results have not come back, at the time this report was written.
column169: Retrain Akzo Nobel's loading personnel in the proper procedures to secure hazardous shipments.

column168: It was reported that while unloading a 330 gallon tote of UN2030 Hydrazine Hydrate, the tote flipped over, releasing an initial unknown amount of material to the concrete dock. No drains, soils, or waterways were impacted. The terminal was evacuated due to the dangerous nature of the released product. Once entry was made by the HazMat team, it was determined that approximately 3 cups of product had released. The tote was uprighted and speedy dry placed on to the spilled product. The product was transferred into a new, clean tote provided from the shipper and all waste was placed into a total of 6 - 55 gallon poly and metal drums with poly lining. The tote was left on-site with a RCRA empty label for the shipper to pickup. All other waste was taken off-site by the contractor for disposal.

Two pick-up trucks were stopped at the beginning of a construction area.  Our Transport came over the hill with a loaded trailer and didn't have time to stop.  He slammed into the back of one truck and pushed that truck into another truck.  Then our transport veered off the roadway and hit a tree.  A small amount of gas from the pickup trucks leaked onto the roadway and a little oil from the transports engine leaked near the tree.  The driver of our transport passed away from the impact of the crash.  Three others that were in the two pick-up trucks were injured.

column168: At 15:00 on September 22, 2016, Triumvirate's driver stopped at a rest stop in Austinburg, OH.  Upon exiting the tractor, the driver conducted an inspection of the trailer and its contents and did not find any issues.  At 17:00, the driver exited the tractor again and noticed a small amount of liquid on one of the tractor tires.  The driver then inspected the outside of the trailer and noticed a small amount of liquid inside the trailer.  The driver called the corporate office and was instructed to place absorbent pads under the area of the leak to contain the material leaking from the trailer.  Our driver then notified the manager of the Pilot rest stop who then called the Austinburg Fire Department.
column169: In order to prevent any similar events, it is imperative that the appropriate shipping container be selected at the time of generation.  It appears by all evidence that this release occurred because the waste material was incompatible with the container type.  The waste was corrosive in nature and overtime caused a hole to form near the bottom of the container, which lead to the release.      The leaked material had been placed in a steel (A1A) closed head container.  Based on the corrosive nature of this mixture, a polyethylene container or a steel container with a polyethylene liner would have been a more appropriate choice for transport.  It appears that a combination of events: corrosion and chemical reaction, resulted in the pencil lead sized failure of the container allowing the contents to spill out.

CAR TTAX 355048    BNSF POLICE WERE NOTIFIED OF POSSIBLE UNDECLARED HAZMAT SHIPMENT IN JW127178 ON FLAT CAR TTAX 355048. BNSF POLICE AND EXPLOSIVE K-9 CHECKED THE EXTERIOR OF THE TRAILER PRIOR TO BNSF HAZMAT PERFORMING AIR MONITORING AROUND THE TRAILER AND DOORS PRIOR TO OPENING. WITH NO IMMEDIATE HAZARDS FOUND, THE REAR DOORS WERE OPENED TO FIND 17 SUPER-SACS OF A CLASS 9, UN3077 MATERIAL. THE MATERIAL CONTAINED WITHIN THE SUPER-SACS WAS IDENTIFIED AS AN ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, SOLID N.O.S (MOLYBDENUM NICKEL OXIDE). THE TRAILER HAD NO PLACARDS NOR WAS THIS HAZMAT DECLARED ON THE WAYBILL, ONLY FAK. SEAL ON THIS TRAILER HAD NO NUMBERS. SEAL WAS CUT TO OPEN AND INVESTIGATE. PICTURES WERE TAKEN AND TRAILER SEALED.      CAR TTRX 377058    BNSF POLICE WERE NOTIFIED OF POSSIBLE UNDECLARED HAZMAT SHIPMENT IN JW127178 ON FLAT CAR TTAX 377058. BNSF POLICE AND EXPLOSIVE K-9 CHECKED THE EXTERIOR OF THE TRAILER PRIOR TO BNSF HAZMAT PERFORMING AIR MONITORING AROUND THE TRAILER AND DOORS PRIOR TO OPENING. WITH NO IMMEDIATE HAZARDS FOUND, THE REAR DOORS WERE OPENED TO FIND 19 PALLETS OF CANNED PUMPKIN PIE FILLING, 3 SUPER SACS OF A CLASS 9, UN3077 MATERIAL, AND 3 55 GALLON METAL OPEN-HEAD DRUMS OF A CLASS 9, 3077 MATERIAL. THE MATERIAL CONTAINED WITHIN BOTH CONTAINER TYPES WAS IDENTIFIED AS AN ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, SOLID N.O.S. (MOLYBDENUM NICKEL OXIDE). THE TRAILER HAD NO PLACARDS NOR WAS THIS HAZMAT SHIPMENT DECLARED ON THE WAYBILL, ONLY AS FAK. THE SEAL ON THIS TRAILER WAS INTACT. THE SEAL WAS CUT TO OPEN AND INVESTIGATE. PICTURES WERE TAKEN AND THE TRAILER WAS SEALED WITH A NEW SEAL.

column168: 9/3/2016:  At approximately 11AM, during routine yard switching operations, a CR engineer noted icing around the protective housing of tank car TILX 301890, containing the residue of Petroleum Gases, Liquefied (Mixed Butanes).      Further inspection by CR A. Richter and CR emergency response contractor, Hepaco, found both liquid valves and the vapor valve not fully closed, with all valves having less than tool tight closure plugs.    Valves were closed, plugs made tool tight and car okayed for forwarding to original destination.      Note:  Car was unloaded and shipped from Tyburn RR Company, Morrisville, PA.

column168: While In-Transit a Clean Harbors driver stopped at TA Truck Stop for fuel and during that time frame he noticed liquid leaking out of his van trailer.  The driver immediately re-positioned his trailer to an area where no other trucks were parked. Clean Harbors response team responded and found a 5 gallon poly pail laying on its side and was leaking from the cap area.  The pail was placed in an Overpack and the flooring inside the van trailer along with asphalt was cleaned up using speedi-dri and other absorbent material.  The overpack and clean up material continued on for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: Reminded facility personnel who are responsible for loading van trailers that all containers need to be properly secured prior to transit.

column168: September 21, 2016:  During routine switching operations in CR's Morrisville, PA yard, it was reported that tank car AHWX 3155, load, Phenol Molten, was wet on top of the car, and small amount of product had run down the sides of the car and dripped inside the gauge of the track in an area approximately 1' x 1'.    Further inspection by CR's S. Hart, Assistant Manager Risk, and Hepaco, CR's emergency response contractor, found all 6 manway cover securement bolts were less than tool tight, allowing product to leak from this area while car was under movement.    Car was isolated on the west end of Track E4 in the yard. Manway cover was opened, manway gasket inspected and found to be in almost new condition. Manway cover was closed and resecured tool tight (shipper seals removed and replaced by Hepaco seals after securement).    Car was decontaminated and cleaned, effected area under car where originally found was also remediated, and car was okayed for transportation.

column168: HAZMAT AUDITOR CAME TO MY STATION AND TOLD ME A PACKAGE ON HIS STATION WAS LEAKING SLIGHTLY. I PUT ON THE RESPONDER SAFETY GEAR AND WENT OVER TO HIS WORK STATION. I FOUND A BOX WITH A WET CORNER AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID LEAKING. THE PACKAGE HAD A CORROSIVE 8 DIAMOND LABEL AND A UN3265 WITH SHIPPING NAME. FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS I NEUTRALIZED THE LEAKED MATERIAL. ABSORBED IT AND TOOK THE PACKAGE AND MATERIAL TO THE DMP CAGE FOR PROCESSING. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER INSIDE I DISCOVERED THE CAP WAS LOOSE AND HAD LEAKED.
column169: I WOULD RECOMMEND THE SHIPPER DOUBLE CHECK THE CAPS ON THE CONTAINERS THEY SEND OUT AS IT IS FAIRLY COMMON TO GET CONTAINERS FROM THEM WITH LOOSE CAPS.

column168: GATX 6125 was discovered leaking spent sulfuric acid at approximately 1935 hours on September 16, 2016 at the PTRA Manchester Yard. Roscoe Compton from Martin Product Sales was notified and approved the response and clean up by M&M Protection.  M&M Protection responded to the scene and found product leaking from the flange on the liquid line.  Once pressure was released from the car the leak stopped however the liquid line flange bolts were fused and could not be removed. PTRA determined the best solution was to move the car to customer track, Westway Terminal, approximately 1/4 mile under 49CFR Part 174.50 for unloading and repair. The car was spotted at approximately  0130 hours on September 17.
column169: Martin Product Sales was notified of the leak at the time of the incident. The car was unloaded by Westway and moved to a repair track.  We have not seen any information concerning the status of the repair to date.

column168: Mechanical Carmen inspecting inbound cut in receiving yard reported GATX 32206 leaking contents.  Approximately 600 liquid gallons of product leaked through the jacket at the bottom of the tank due to multiple points of interior liner corrosion on the B-end tank head.  BNSF Hazmat personnel, ER contractors, and the local Fire Department responded to the incident.  The receiving yard was evacuated for about 4 hours.  One of the Mechanical Carmen who reported GATX 32206 leaking indicated difficulty breathing and sought medical attention, so he was transported to a local hospital for examination and released with no medical treatment.  GATX 32206 was ultimately transloaded and cleaned for further disposition.
column169: GATX 32206 was due for a liner inspection in 2017.  I would recommend the car owner of GATX 32206 review the last liner inspection details.  A proper exterior inspection before and prior to offering for shipment may have identified the release potentially by identifying exterior points of corrosion on the jacket itself.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: The shipment of hidden dangerous goods was tendered to IBC Airways from DHL Express on its ramp at Miami International Airport.  the shipment in question was a single pallet, wrapped completely in black shrink-wrap and was loaded onto an IBC cargo aircraft by forklift.  The pallet was then secured in the cargo bay by straps and transported to Lynden Pindling International Airport in Nassau, Bahamas.    During the supervised off-loading procedure at Odyssey Aviation, ground personnel with the use of a forklift were removing the pallet from the aircraft when the fiberboard packaging gave way causing two of the hidden gas cylinders to fall from the pallet and strike the ground.  Neither cylinder discharged.    At the flight crews instruction, no further attempt was made to remove the pallet from the aircraft.  Ground personnel were instructed to remove the remaining cylinders by hand, one by one, and place them on a another pallet on the ground.  During this process, another portion of the packaging gave way, causing one more cylinder to fall from the pallet and strike the ground.  This cylinder did discharge.    No individual on the ground suffered any injury or effect from this occurrence and the discharge dissipated into the atmosphere.
column169: As the shipment was hidden and not declared as dangerous goods, no specific changes to current procedures are warranted.  Extreme vigilance is mandated for all company personnel that handle DG and current company training includes procedures and techniques for hidden shipment indicators.

column4: A specification cargo tank 1,000 gallons or greater containing any hazardous materials that (1) received structural damage to the lading retention system or damage that requires repair to a system int
column168: KERN OIL PERSONNEL WERE STAGING RAIL CARS ON INTERNAL TRACK WITH THE USE OF A "SHUTTLE-WAGON" RAIL CAR MOVER. A SET OF THREE CARS, CONTAINING TANK CAR CBTX 727777, WAS SPOTTED ONTO KERN TRACK 3. PERSONNEL THEN PROCEEDED TO CONNECT TO A SECOND SET OF CARS IN ORDER TO SPOT THEM ON KERN TRACK 5; THIS SET CONTAINED CAR NATX 400557. THE SPOTTER INDICATED TO THE SHUTTLE-WAGON DRIVER THAT HE HAD THE ALL CLEAR TO MOVE SOUTH TOWARD TRACK 5 IT BECAME APPARENT THAT THE CARS STAGED ON TRACK 3 HAD NOT BEEN PLACED SUFFICIENTLY BEHIND THE CLEARANCE LINE, AND THERE WAS NOT ADEQUATE CLEARANCE TO PROCEED WITH SECOND SET. THE SPOTTER RADIOED FOR THE SHUTTLE-WAGON DRIVER TO STOP, BUT THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH TIME AND THE CARS COLLIDED.     NEITHER TANK CAR FAILED AS A RESULT OF THE DAMAGE INCURRED. TANK CARS CBTX 727777 AND NATX 400557 BOTH INCURRED DAMAGE TO THE PLATFORM, AIR BRKAES, AND A RIPPLING TO THE OUTER SHELL.    ADDITIONAL INFORMATION PERTAINING TO SECOND TANK CAR INVOLVED CBTX 727777;  11. SHIPPER: TAUBER PETROCHEMICAL PO BOX 4645, HOUSTON, TX 77210  12. ORIGIN: INTERCONTINENTAL TERMINALS, 2627 TIDAL ROAD, DEER PARK, TX 77536  14. PSN:TOLUENE 15: TECHNICAL/TRADE NAME: TOLUENE 16. HAZARD CLASS: 3 17. UN 1294  18. PG: II  26a. PACKAGING IDENTIFICATION MARKINGS: DOT 111A100W1  27. PACKAGE CAPACITY: 29,250 USG AMOUNT IN PACKAGE: 28,992 USG  28. PACKAGING CONSTRUCTION AND TESTING: LAST TEST DATE 2014.
column169: KERN IMMEDIATELY BEGAN AN INVESTIGATION INTO THE EVENT. RECOMMENDATIONS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FROM THIS INVESTIGATION INCLUDE:    1. UPDATING RAILCAR SAFETY AND OPERATIONS PROCEDURES TO INCLUDE ADDITIONAL INFORMATION ON CLEARANCE LINES, SPOTTER RESPONSIBILITIES, SHUTTLE-WAGON DRIVER RESPONSIBILITIES, PRE-MOVEMENT CONFERENCE BETWEEN SPOTTER AND SHUTTLE-WAGON DRIVER, AND IMPROVEMENT TO SYSTEM FOR 3-WAY COMMUNICATIONS.     2. CONDUCTING TRAINING ON UPDATED PROCEDURE FOLLOWING COMPLETION OF ITEM 1.     3. CONDUCTING ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON OPERATION OF SHUTTLE-WAGON TO IMPROVE FAMILIARITY AND PROFICIENCY.     4. EVALUATING RADIO UPGRADE FOR IMPROVED RELIABILITY OF COMMUNICATIONS BETWEEN SHUTTLE-WAGON DRIVER AND SPOTTER.     5. CONSIDER INSTALLATION OF VIDEO MONITORING EQUIPMENT.     6. ENSURING CLEARANCE LINES ARE PAINTED WITH HIGH VISIBILITY WHITE PAINT.

column168: PACKAGE HAD NO OUTER MARKINGS INDICATING CONTENTS. ONCE BOX WAS OPENED, DISCOVERED BOTTLE WITH OXIDIZER 5.1 LABEL ON BOTTLE. FOLLOWED DECISION TREE APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET FOR CLEAN UP OF MATERIALS.
column169: LID WAS NOT TIGHT ON CONTAINER, BOTTLE WAS IN A BOX LAYING ON IT'S SIDE. NO ORIENTATION ARROWS ON CONTAINER.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO PICK UP A LEAKER ON ROAD. THE BOX WAS ON THE 2ND SHELF HAD LEAKED ON TWO OTHER PKGS. THE LEAKING PKG WAS COVERED IN A BLACK PLASTIC SO THAT YOU COULD NOT SEE THE ACTUAL BOX. THE ONLY MARKINGS ON THE PLASTIC WAS ONE HAND DRAWN ARROW ON ONE SIDE OF THE BOX. ONCE I WAS BACK IN THE CAGE, I UNWRAPPED THE BLACK PLASTIC FROM THE BOX TO FIND THAT THE BOX HAD A LIMITED QUANTITY DIAMOND LABEL ON ONE SIDE A PRODUCT LABEL ON THE OTHER SIDE. I STOPPED AND TOOK PICTURES, THEN PROCESSED ALL THE CONTENTS TRHU THE DMP. INSIDE THE BOX I FOUND, TWO 1 GAL CANS OF TOUCHSTONE EDGE SYSTEM PARTS A AND 1 CAN OF TOUCHSTONE EDGE SYSTEM PART B. EACH CAN WAS INDIVIDUALLY WRAPPED IN THE SAME BLACK PLASTIC. THERE WAS NO PADDING, THE CANS WERE DENTED FROM BANGING AGAINST EACH OTHER AND THE LID WERE UP A BIT.
NON HAZMAT LEAKED, AEROSOLS DISCOVERED

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON S15 PSC SLIDE WET. AREA WAS RESTRICTED AND A DESIGNATED RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER RESPONDED USING THEIR DECISION TREE, RESPONSE SHEETS, AND PPE. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER CLEANED UP AND TRANSPORTED THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. MATERIAL WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.
IT WAS FOUND ON ORANGE BELT LEAKING POST SORT. LEAKING FROM CAP. LOOSE CAP AND SEAL CAME UNDONE DUE TO SPILL.
column169: CONTACT SHIPPER TO SECURE CAP AND SEAL FOR SHIPPING.

column168: It was reported that during unloading terminal personnel discover 4-5 gallon metal pails of UN12101 Printing Ink were leaking upon arrival. The cause of the release was that the pails were shrink wrapped too tight and the lid came off. The pails released about 5 gallons to the trailer (985490) floor. An environmental contractor was utilized to clean the release and manage all waste generated.

A/C 7AV operating T56 to LHR air interrupted back to MIA for a odor in the cabin/cockpit. A/C was removed from service and irt was determined that there was an unknown spill in the fwd cargo hold at position 24,25. The a/c was removed from service and SWS Environmental was called. SWS arrived on location at 1330 0n 9/3/16 and was escorted to the a/c. Subsequent investigation of spill by SWS determined that the spill was of an oil based product with a PH value of neutral. The floorboards of the bin were cleaned by SWS and the floorboards removed by a/c mtc. The insulation blankets were contaminated with the same product and removed by SWS. The area has been cleaned and SWS has departed the facility. The contaminated material has been packaged and labeled by SWS in a plastic 50 gal drum and has been moved the the hangar Satellite accumulation area. New insulation material will be locally manufactured and the floorboards reinstalled by a/c mtc. The reported qty of the spill is approx 5 gals.

column168: WASTE SHIPMENT WAS ON ROUTE THROUGH OHIO ON I-80, DRIVER PULLED OVER TO CHECK LOAD AND FOUND MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. DRIVER CALL POLICE AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE 24 CONTACT NUMBER. THE STATE POLICE AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GROUP RESPONDED TO THE CALL. THE CLEAN UP LASTED APPROXIMATELY 2 AND HALF HOURS. THE AREA OUTSIDE THE TRUCK, TRUCK INSIDE AND THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GROUP FOUND THE METAL DRUM LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE TOTAL VOLUME ESTIMATED AT 25 GALLONS. MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND SCRAPED UP AS WELL, AND THE APPROXIMATELY 50LB OF CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS REMOVED. APPROXIMATELY 28 GALLONS OF WASTE ACETONE REMAINED IN THE DRUM. AFTER OFFLOADING THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO CONTAINMENT WHERE THE LIQUID WAS ABSORBED AND REMOVED.

column168: THE HANDLER NOTED THAT A PACKAGE TRAVERSING DOWN THE BELT WAS LEAKING A WHITE SUBSTANCE. THE LEAK CAUSED DAMAGE TO APPROXIMATELY 20 ADDITIONAL PACKAGES. UPON DISCOVERY THE BELT WAS HALTED AMD THE DAMAGE SHIPMENTS REMOVED. THE SPILL SPECIALIST ADDRESSED THE SPILL USING SCU PROCEDURES. THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED AND A ONE GALLON PAINT CAN WAS DISCOVERED WITH NO CLIPS AND NO SEALS LEAKED ON TWO OTHER PLASTIC GALLON BOTTLES OF LACQUER INSIDE. THE FAA AND CUSTOMER CONTACT WAS INITIATED, BY DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION. THE SHIPMENT WAS BAGGED AND DRUMMED WITH OTHER DAMAGED PACKAGING FOR FAA REVIEW.

column168: It was reported that terminal personnel discovered a metal tote of UN1263 paint was found leaking on the dock due to a faulty valve. There was a very slow leak and the tote released about 12 ounces. An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release, transfer the material into a tote, and manage all waste.

Tank Car BNSF 880225 was reported releasing product in the rail yard from the top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV).  The BNSF responder reported the leak source was at BNSF 880225's TOBOV bottom outlet valve flange bolts.  The TOBOV was found less than tool tight.  BNSF responder properly tightened the TOBOV, which mitigated any further release of product.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste was on the dock at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  During a routine dock check, it was noticed that black liquid was seeping from tape that had been placed around the seams of 2 of 3 overpack drums that were used to ship the waste.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and placed the material into suitable salvage containers, along with the material used to clean up the spilled material.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The customer shipped the material as a solid but there was liquid asphalt that oozed out of the seam.  The drum was not closed properly (tape) and should not have been picked up.  The driver was disciplined for failure to inspect the container prior to picking up and retrained in proper container selection.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: On September 28, 2016 at 1450 ET, during unloading operations, the terminal personnel discovered a cracked (1) 55-gallon steel drum of UN1210 Printing Ink "Propak" during a forklift accident. Approximately 1-pint released to the concrete dock floor. A contractor was dispatched who contained and cleaned the release by utilizing absorbents. All impacted adsorbents were containerized into a (1) 55-gallon steel drum and taken offsite for proper disposal. The damaged drum was overpacked into a steel overpack drum and was staged onsite in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

At 0530 ET on 9/24/2016 a Schneider Bulk tractor trailer rolled over, resulting in the release of an unknown amount of diesel fuel to the roadside soil. The truck was also hauling a tanker, which contained Vinyl Acetate Monomer. It was reported that it was leaking from the tank lid at an approximate rate of 1 gallon per 5 minutes.  In total, an estimated 10 gallons of product released.
column169: Better training may have prevented the rolloff incident

ERTS was contacted by David Ondik of Estes regarding an unknown release inside of trailer #285198 at their terminal at; 221 Church Road. York, PA 17406. It was reported that about 3 gallons of an unknown material has released from the trailer to the asphalt below. A 55 gallon poly drum of UN2922 Corrosive Liquid NOS ( Chromium Trioxide / Liquid Chromic Acid 40% ) The contractor pH'd the liquid and it registered a 2. The damaged drum will be over packed into a poly drum.

column168: ECLX 75458 WAS NOTED TO BE HISSING BY CP PERSONNEL. AT THAT POINT THE HAZ-MAT MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED. CP CALLED CONTRACTORS TO INVESTIGATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM THE TELL TALE VALVE ON THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. DUE TO THE DESIGN OF THE VALVE A LEAK FROM THE TELL TALE INDICATES THAT THE RUPTURE DISC HAD BEEN COMPROMISED AND WOULD NEED TO BE REMOVED TO BE REPLACED AND THE TANK BUBBLE TESTED. THE CAR WAS PURGED AND THE OLD VALVE WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED. THE RUPTURED DISC WAS FRACTURED CAUSING THE LEAK. ONCE THE NEW VALVE WAS REPLACED THE CAR WAS BUBBLE TESTED. THE CAR PASSED AND WAS RELEASED.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On September 27, 2016, a FedEx Freight driver reported FXFZ 974561 actively leaking when he/she attempted to outgate. The FedEx Freight driver was directed to park the unit in the containment pit. Chemical Helpline was contacted for assistance; Patriot Environmental was dispatched to remediate the leak at the facility.     Patriot Environmental determined leaking product was a 1/2 gallon of the UN3264* material listed on the waybill. The leak originated from one (1) of the three (3) 15 gallon drums poorly secured with two strips of stretch wrap at the rear; straps utilized to keep the pallet in place were loose. Patriot staff neutralized product and cleaned the floor as well as the exterior of the trailer. The 15 gallon drum was over-packed into a 55 gallon drum for transit to the nearest FedEx Freight facility. New seal number applied was 2449047.     *The material was labeled in FXFZ 974561 as UN1824 (Sodium Hydroxide solution).  FedEx Freight clarified that the container label was not correct, however the shipping description did correspond with the actual material contained in the drums.
column169: The load was not properly secured, BNSF notified FedEx of the condition for appropriate handling and review as necessary.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Tank car GATX 8043 was reported to have released an undetermined amount of sulfuric acid from the top of the car in the UPRR yard in Salina, KS.  The released acid dripped onto a UPRR switchmans head, hands, arms and leg causing chemical burns.      Inspection of the tank car found approximately five to ten gallons of product had splashed across the top of the tank car and run down the sides of the car in some spots.  Further inspection found the pressure plate/ fixed manway cover plate gasket out of position on the B-end of the tank car.  The gasket was hanging out between the tank car nozzle and the manway cover plate.  In addition, two of twelve manway cover plate securement bolts (on the same end as the gasket was displaced) were slightly less than tool tight.      There was no evidence of a release from the fill port or frangible disk housing.  The fill port gasket was visually checked from the side and determined to be in position.     Haz-Mat Response (Contractor) responded and decontaminated the ground and tank car with approximately fifty gallons of soda ash/water solution.  The tank car was secured and later transferred into a second tank car provided by Norfalco/Glencore (Shipper).  No other remediation was required.

column168: 26SEP16  Undeclared Lithium Metal Batteries (Energizer Lithium Metal Batteries Type 123 and Panasonic Lithium Metal Batteries type CR123A)  loose in packaging,(exceeding amount allowable and not in original manufacturers packaging,) discovered in packages under Lufthansa Cargo Airway bill number 020-71491125,This discovery was in conjunction with completing TSA screening requirements for uplift on a Lufthansa Passenger Aircraft 26 SEP 16. Description on Airway bill only listed Show Material. Shipment stopped and returned to CEVA logistics Aurora Colorado for corrective action.  27 SEP 16  Shipment returned to Lufthansa Cargo Denver under same Airway bill with advise from CEVA representatives that corrective action had been taken and all Batteries had been removed. Again found shipment still contained Lithium Metal Batteries (same type and description above) still contained in shipment.   with results from screening process and physical check of consignment to confirm non-compliance with DGR IATA regulation and Manufacture Product Safety Data Sheets   Lufthansa Cargo Notified FAA Special Agent Carlee Cellar to confirm next action 27SEP16
column169: Lufthansa Cargo   Will continue to use proactive actions to stop undeclared shipments before an accident can occurs

column17: WEST BEND TRANSIT AND SERVICE COMPANY
column168: DRIVER WAS NOTIFIED VIA PHONE THAT THERE WAS SMOKE COMING FROM BACK OF HIS TRAILER THE DRIVER SAFELY PULL OVER ONTO THE SHOULDER OF ROADWAY AND INSPECTED THE SOURCE OF THE SMOKE. IT WAS AT THIS TIME HE DISCOVERED HEATED BRAKE HE WENT BACK TO HIS TRUCK TO RETRIEVE AN EXTINGUISHER TO PUT OUT THE FLAME. INITIAL ATTEMPT PUT OUT THE FIRE BUT IT STARTED BACK UP AND INTENSIFIED THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO USE EXTINGUISHER AGAIN UNTIL IT WAS EMPTY HE THEN RAN BACK TO TRUCK AND USED WHAT WATER HE HAD, THE FIRE INCREASED IN INTENSITY AND THAT IS WHEN THE DRIVER UNHOOKED THE POWER UNIT TO PREVENT MORE DAMAGE. BY THE TIME THE FIRE SAFETY TEAMS ARRIVED THE TRAILER WAS COMPLETELY ENGULFED IN FLAMES, AT THIS TIME WE STARTED TO IDENTIFY CARGO AND REPORTED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ABOARD. SET ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO SECURE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND CLEAN UP. CONTAINMENT LASTED AN ESTIMATED 4-5 HOURS AND THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP WAS ESTIMATED AT 10-12 HOURS. THE PACKAGING CONSISTED OF 160 PAPER BAGS FILL WITH SODIUM CARBONATE IT'S MY BELIEF THAT THE PACKAGES DIDN'T FAIL IT WAS THE FIRE AND THE ITEMS USED TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE THAT CAUSED THE HAZARDOUS SPILL.
column169: WEST BEND TRANSIT IS IMMEDIATELY GATHERING ADDITIONAL TRAINING VIDEOS AND WRITTEN TESTS TO REVIEW WITH ALL OF OUR EMPLOYEES ON PROPER PROCEDURES WHEN A SITUATION SUCH AS THIS HAS OCCURRED. WEST BEND TRANSIT WILL ALSO MAKE IT A PART OF THE NEW TRAINING HOW TO PERFORM PROPER BRAKE INSPECTION BEFORE, DURING AND AFTER EACH LOAD TRANSFER AND TO IDENTIFY POTENTIAL SAFETY ISSUES.

column168: AS HARCROS TRAILER #554 WAS BEING UNLOADED AT TG MISSOURI (CUSTOMER SITE) THE FORKLIFT DRIVER EMPLOYED BY TG MISSOURI PUNCTURED A DRUM OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID WITH THE FORK. THE DRUM LEAKED OUT APPROX. 40 GALLONS OF MATERIAL INSIDE OF THE TRAILER. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE CUSTOMER BUT HAS LIKELY CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE STRUCTURE OF THE TRAILER SINCE THE CHEMICAL REACHED WOOD FLOORING, ALUMINUM SIDE CHANNEL, UNDER FRAMING AND REAR BUMPER. THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO TANK TRAILER FOR CLEANING AND WAS TAKEN TO CSTK FOR EVALUATION OF THE DAMAGE.
column169: THIS ACCIDENT WAS NOT CAUSED BY AN EMPLOYEE OF HARCROS CHEMICALS INC.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: At approximately 15:30 MST on 9/29/16, during an inspection of cars in the yard, FRA inspector Isaac Bonds found the CTCX 732100 to have leaked a small amount of liquid from the liquid line valve flange area.  Mr. Bonds notified BNSF personnel.  BNSF Hazmat responders inspected the area and found that the liquid had evaporated, flange securement nuts were inspected and found to be tool tight.  No active leak was found.  The car was moved within yard limits to the industry track for off-loading and preparation for repairs or to be sent to shop.  As the liquid valve was not removed, the exact cause of the release is unknown but suspected to be an issue with the sealing surface of the liquid line flange.
column169: Shipper has been notified of the condition, repair and inspection records should be verified to ensure that procedures are in place to detect and prevent releases from the valve flange areas.

AREA, ALONG WITH OTHER PACKAGES THAT WERE SPILLED ON BY THE LEAKING PACKAGE, FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. DOMINION IS ISSUING AN ALERT TO ALL FIELD EMPLOYEES OF THE FACT SURROUND THE INCIDENT AND COMMUNICATING THE EXPECTATION GOING FORWARD.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Human Error
column168: THE DRIVER LOADED A PALLET JACK AND PALLET OF SPENT LEAD ACID BATTERIES THAT HE JUST PICKED UP FORM A CUSTOMER, ONTO THE LIFT GATE OF HIS TRUCK. HE THEN WENT BACK INTO THE CUSTOMER TO LET THEM KNOW THEY WILL BE GETTING A NEW DRIVER. HE CAME OUT OF THE FRONT DOOR OF THE CUSTOMER’S OFFICE AND GOT INTO HIS TRUCK. NOT REMEMBERING THAT HE NEVER LOADED THE BATTERIES. THEY WERE STILL SITTING ON THE LIFT GATE WHEN HE PULLED AWAY FROM THE CUSTOMER.     WHILE DRIVING DOWN THE HIGHWAY, THE DRIVER WAS FLAGGED DOWN BY A PASSERBY TO LET HIM KNOW THAT HIS LIFT GATE WAS STILL DOWN. HE PULLED OVER AND WHILE CLOSING THE LIFT GATE THE POLICE STOPPED AND INFORMED HIM ABOUT THE INCIDENT. THE WAS TOLD TO GO TO A TRUCK STOP IN WARREN, OK AND WAIT FOR THE STATE POLICE TO ESCORT HIM BACK TO THE INCIDENT.   THE PALLET JACK AND THE PALLET OF SPENT LEAD ACID BATTERIES FELL OFF THE LIFT GATE WHILE THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING DOWN THE ROAD. THE BATTERIES SCATTERED APPROXIMATELY 300 FEET IN LENGTH AND APPROXIMATELY 45 FEET WIDTH ON THE ROADWAY AND IN AN ADJACENT PARKING LOT. SOME OF THE BATTERIES WERE RUPTURED AND LEAKING. ONE OF THE BATTERIES HIT A PARKED CAR IN THE PARKING LOT. ANOTHER CAR, DRIVING DOWN THE HIGHWAY, DROVE OVER A BATTERY LYING IN THE ROAD WHICH CAUSED UNDER CARRIAGE DAMAGE TO THE CAR AND DEPLOYED THE AIR BAGS. THIS PERSON ALSO HAD SOME MINOR INJURIES.     THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT SHOWED UP TO MITIGATE THE SCENE. THE OKLAHOMA HIGHWAY PATROL DISPATCHED SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICE IN REFERENCE TO A REQUEST FROM THE OKLAHOMA EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT FOR THE ACTUAL CLEAN-UP OF THE BATTERIES. NONE OF THE BATTERIES OR CONTENTS OF THE BATTERIES GOT INTO ANY STREAMS OR STORM DRAINS. THE BATTERIES AND BATTERY PIECES WERE PICKED UP AND PLACED INTO A GAYLORD BOX LINED WITH A 6 MIL PLASTIC BAG. THE BOTTOM OF THE BAG WAS LINED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND LIME MATERIAL TO ABSORB ANY LEAKAGE. THE ROAD AND PARKING LOT WERE ALSO CLEANED UP USING AN ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THIS TOO WAS PLACED INTO THE GAYLORD BOXES.     SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICE TOOK THE BOXES BACK TO THEIR SHOP. THEY REPACKAGED THE BATTERIES AND BATTERY PIECES INTO OVER PACK DRUMS FOR EASIER TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. EAST PENN MANUFACTURING WILL PICK UP THE DRUMS AND TRANSPORT THEM TO A SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS COACHED ON THE PROPER WAY TO LOAD AND UNLOAD A SECURED LOAD PER DOT GUIDELINES. IT WAS ALSO EXPLAINED TO HIM HOW IMPORTANT IT IS TO ALWAYS CONDUCT A THOROUGH SECUREMENT CHECK PRIOR TO LEAVING ANY LOCATION.

column168: Driver connected the delivery hoses for a tractor mounted pump unloading. After a few minutes he didn’t think product was flowing from the cargo tank to the tractor mounted pump. He suspected the pump was air locked. He released one ear of the camlock fitting on the product hose to bleed the air pressure. The hose slipped and the second ear disconnected allowing the hose to completely disconnect releasing 20-30 gallons of product in the unloading containment area and on the driver. Driver was put in the emergency shower and then taken to a local hospital to be checked as a precaution. No treatment was required.

column25: RIBOST TERMINAL LLC DBA WORLD OIL TERMINALS  LONG BEACH
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HOURS ON SEPTEMBER 4, 2016, A WORLD OIL TRANSPORTATION TRUCK WAS PREPARING TO LOAD CRUDE OIL FROM WORLD OIL TERMINALS' LOADING RACK. AT THE BEGINNING OF THE LOADING PROCESS THE DRIVER FAILED TO VERIFY THAT ALL VALVES ON THE HEADER SYSTEM OF THE TRAILER WERE OPEN TO ASSURE THAT THE PRODUCT HAD A CLEAR PATH TO THE FRONT COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER. THE PRODUCT BEING LOADED FOUND THE PATH OF LEAST RESISTANCE AND WHILE PRESSURING THE HEADER SYSTEM AGAINST A CLOSED VALVE. THE 4" CAMELOCK CAP ON THE HEADER PIPING LOCATED ON THE DRIVER SIDE OF THE TRAILER POPPED OFF, AND ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO CONCRETE WITHIN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THE LOADING VALVE WAS CLOSED IMMEDIATELY, SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 355 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL ONTO CONCRETE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IMMEDIATELY WITHIN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AND CLEANED WITHIN 2 HOURS OF THE INCIDENT. NO INJURIES WERE RECORDED AND NO WATERWAYS OR LAND WERE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE. IN RESPONSE TO THE SPILL, WORLD OIL TERMINAL OPERATION'S TEAM IMMEDIATELY STOPPED TRUCK/VEHICLE TRAFFIC IN THE AREA. THE LOADING PROCESS OF THE RACK WAS STOPPED UNTIL CLEAN-UP AND VERIFICATION OF LOADING ARM WAS COMPLETED.
column169: WORLD OIL TRANSPORTATION POSTPONED THE TANKER TRUCK FROM OPERATIONS UNTIL A FULL MECHANICAL VERIFICATION WAS COMPLETED. SINCE THE INCIDENT, OPERATING PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN REVIEWED WITH WORLD OIL TRANSPORTATION DRIVERS.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS EB ON IS 80 AT MP 228 AT 0600HRS. TRAVELING IN A REDUCED LANE CONSTRUCTION ZONE, DRIVER STATE HE HIT A POTHOLE ON THE ROADWAY, TRAVELED OFF THE RIGHT EDGE STRIKING A SOFT BERM, PULLED HIM ONTO A SLIGHT DOWNWARD SLOPE WHICH CAUSED THE LIQUID GASOLINE TO SLOSH TO THE EXTREME RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER CAUSING IT TO ROLLOVER INTO A MUDDY DITCH. THE TANK APPARENTLY RUPTURED AT THAT POINT, RELEASING THE GASOLINE, WHICH THEN FOUND AN IGNITION SOURCE AND CAUGHT FIRE. TWO VEHICLES STOPPED TO ASSIST OUR DRIVER, NEITHER OF THEM WERE INVOLVED IN THE CRASH, BOTH VEHICLES WERE DESTROYED IN THE FIRE, ALONG WITH OUR TRACTOR AND TRAILER. THERE WERE NO INJURIES RESULTING FROM THE INCIDENT.
column169: AFTER THIS INCIDENT, THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ABOUT DRIVING IN A CONSTRUCTION ZONE AND USING EXTREME CAUTION. ALTHOUGH HE WAS AT OR BELOW SPEED LIMIT. OUR DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO SLOW DOWN BELOW THE POSTED SPEED LIMIT, AND USE THE LANE FURTHEST AWAY FROM THE BERM, WHEN PERMITTED TO USE THE LEFT LANE.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING BAG PUNCTURED BAG PLACED INTO LINED SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. SPILLAGE MANAGED PROPERLY. REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT MOVED ON TO CONSIGNEE.
column169: TERMINAL MANAGEMENT SHOULD RETRAIN RESPONSIBLE EMPLOYEE TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S., WITH FLASH POINT ABOVE 37.8 C, AT OR ABOVE ITS FLASH POINT
column168: TANKER WAS TRANSFERRING LIQUID SEALER TO A HOLDING TANK. A COUPLER FITTING CRACKED AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SPRAY ONTO PUMP MOTOR, CAUSING FIRE. THE VALVE WAS QUICKLY SHUT OFF. THE BENSALEM FIRE & RESCUE EXTINGUISHED THE FLAMES. THE TANKER DID NOT RUPTURE.
column169: WE NO LONGER TRANSPORT THIS PRODUCT FOR HENRY CO.(OR ANY OTHER COMPANY). THIS WAS AN OCCASIONAL JOB THAT WE DID FOR A NEIGHBORING COMPANY FOR THE PAST 10 YEARS. OUR PRIMARY BUSINESS IS HOME HEATING OIL DELIVERY.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE, WITH NOT MORE THAN 0.2%  OF COMBUSTIBLE MATERIALS, INCLUDING ANY ORGANIC SUBSTANCE CALCULATED AS CARBON TO THE EXCLUSION OF ANY OTHER ADDED SUBSTANCE
column168: DRIVER CAME UP ON STOPPED TRAFFIC AND HE TURNED RIGHT INTO A CHURCH PARKING LOT TO AVOID A REAR END COLLISION. THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRUCK HIT A DITCH THAT CAUSED THE TRUCK TO LAY OVER ON IT SIDE. A PASSENGER CALLED 911 AND THE DRIVER CALLED ME. I THEN HEADED TO THE ACCIDENT. THE COVER ON THE AMMONIUM NITRATE (AN) WAS BENT WITH AN OPENING OF APPROX. 3” (AN) PRILLS WAS SPILLING OUT ONTO THE ASPHALT OF THE PARKING LOT. IT PROBABLY CONTINUED TO SPILL FOR APPROX. 20 MINUTES. 2,400 LBS OF PRILLS WAS ON THE ASPHALT. ONCE THE PRILLS FELL DOWN PASS THE OPENING OF THE COVER, IT COMPLETELY STOPPED. THE BIN HAD AROUND 6,000 LBS TOTAL IN IT.
column169: SINCE THIS ACCIDENT, WE HAVE WENT OVER WHAT HAPPENED HERE, AND RETRAINED OUR DRIVERS. WE EMPHASIZED OUR DRIVER TO SLOW DOWN, BE MORE AWARE OF THEIR SURROUNDING AT ALL TIMES AND TRY TO AVOID ANY SOFT AREA OR DITCH, THAT MAY CAUSE A TRUCK TO LAY OVER.

column168: Event # 66032..    No package failure..  Consignee error..     He states he arrived at consignee and they indicated there was enough room to accept the full load of product.. He hooked up and unloaded and the trailer was almost empty when the product began to drip down the side of the tank.. Consignee misjudged the amount of room they had in the tank.. Tank overflowed..  Consignee employee rinsed it off and no further clean up was needed..
